                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d43">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.62114 Sick/14: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Sweden</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stockholm</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-08-10T22:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 10, 1943—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 11—2:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2504. Subject matter Department’s 861, August 6, 8 p.m., and 862, August 6, 9
                        p.m.<note n="18" xml:id="d43fn18">Latter not printed.</note> has been taken
                    up with Foreign Office. Secretary General informed me today that he has
                    authorization from Prime Minister to say that Swedish Government not only has no
                    objection to use of port of Goteborg for purposes planned but will be glad to be
                    of any possible assistance in effecting exchange of wounded war prisoners.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
